    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense, but these leaks are really hard to catch because they aren't tied to one specific function call. it feels like there's just something tiny and intermittent happening in the background and then it scales up. do you have any advice for how to track down those really subtle, hidden leaks that don't show up in simple code reviews? maybe some ways to instrument the code to see where the \"hidden\" growth is coming from?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "For subtle, hidden leaks, you can instrument your code to log memory allocations and deallocations. Use a logging library or implement your own wrapper classes for memory management functions to keep track of all allocations and deallocations. An example is to log the memory address of allocated memory regions or the size of the allocation. You can also look into memory profiling tools that can collect detailed information about memory usage over time, such as `llvmtop` or ` ketogenic`, and have them write memory allocations and deallocations to log files.\n\nTo make the instrumentation reusable, you can encapsulate the logging functionality into a logger class that can be injected into your components.",
      "source": "target",
